TI  - Design, Development, and Evaluation of an Intelligent Generation System for Contextualized Primary School Science Test Questions
AU  - Yang, X.
AU  - Wen, Y.
AU  - Zhang, X.
AU  - Zhan, Z.
T2  - 8th International Conference on Educational Technology Management, ICETM 2025
AB  - To solve the problems of low efficiency and uneven quality in the traditional manual creation of context-based science questions for primary schools, this study designed and validated an intelligent generation system named 'SciQ-Gen'. The system uses a large language model as its core. It introduces an innovative 'Dual-channel Retrieval-Augmented Generation' framework to improve both the engagement of the scenarios and the scientific accuracy. The system also uses a 'Generate-Evaluate-Revise' iterative process for quality control. Furthermore, this research developed a quality evaluation framework for test questions that includes four dimensions: 'scenario quality', 'question quality', 'knowledge and skill depth', and 'inquiry level'. In a comparative experiment, three experts used this framework to anonymously score questions from three sources: those generated by SciQ-Gen, those from regional public examinations, and those from international assessments such as PISA and TIMSS. The research confirmed that questions generated by SciQ-Gen performed exceptionally well in 'depth of knowledge and skills' and 'inquiry level'. However, their performance in 'scenario quality' and 'question quality' was slightly weaker than the questions from the international assessments. The study also shows that its evaluation framework provides a scientific and practical standard for assessing context-based test questions. © 2025 IEEE.
