TI  - Parameter Efficient Fine-Tuning of LLMs Enhanced with RAG to Assist Students with Lectures
AU  - Jiyadh, I.
AU  - Thirukumaran, S.
AU  - Ratnarajah, N.
T2  - Proceedings of ICITR 2025 - 10th International Conference on Information Technology Research: Advancing Global Connectivity Through Emerging Information Technology Solutions
AB  - Lecturing is the primary method of delivering valuable information to students across universities and other educational settings. Taking notes effectively during lectures is crucial, as it helps students understand later and provides a reliable resource for revision and exam preparation. However, it is a cognitively complex task requiring the students to attentively listen while capturing important details delivered during lectures. Despite these, students often face difficulties during lectures due to environmental factors, teaching methods, peer influence and technical issues, all of which hinder engagement and effective note-taking. Especially for students with learning disabilities, note-taking could be hard. Existing GenAI-based systems either rely on proprietary LLMs requiring certain subscriptions or a keyword extraction mechanism, and provide inadequate support to students who forget learned facts after lectures. In this paper, we propose an automated tool that integrates ASR, an LLM fine-tuned using parameter-efficient techniques and RAG. This tool assists students by producing detailed lecture notes highlighting important announcements, answering students' questions related to past lectures and generating theoretical questions on lectures held so far to improve students' comprehension. It demonstrates that high-quality, accessible lecture assistance tools can be built even on modest hardware to support students with lectures. We also analysed the ability of LLM to handle large prompts and compared its response with and without RAG integration. The findings indicate that simply increasing the context length does not improve LLM's ability to handle large prompts, while RAG integration significantly reduced the hallucination rate by 37%. © 2025 IEEE.
