TI  - RAG Technology to Develop and Evaluate an Automatic Generation System for Similar Problems with Adjustable Difficulty
AU  - Takeuchi, A.
AU  - Takagi, M.
T2  - Proceedings - 9th International Conference on Information Technology, InCIT 2025
AB  - This study proposes a system that automatically generates analogous problems tailored to a user's subjective sense of difficulty using large language models (LLMs) and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) technology. While automatic generation systems are expected to reduce the burden on instructors for developing practice problems, they have limited versatility and struggle to adjust the level of difficulty of the generated problems. Our proposed system establishes a diagnostic phase that first collects a user's difficulty evaluation data, followed by a problem-generation phase that attempts to adjust the difficulty in line with the user's intent by providing the relevant data to an LLM as few-shot examples. The results of our experiments confirmed that this method significantly improves the difficulty agreement rate from 38.1% in the diagnostic phase to 81.0% in the problem-generation phase. We also found that through the optimization of the similarity threshold in RAG and prompt engineering, it is possible to achieve a problem validity rate of over 90% and prevent the content from deviating beyond the scope of the educational materials. By introducing a feedback loop into the system that incorporates user subjectivity, this research contributes to alleviating the burden of problem creation in educational settings and supporting personalized learning.  © 2025 IEEE.
